4.Text: CH4 Gas Limited ("CH4") is a Queensland based energy company focused on the development
and commercialization of Australian coal seam gas resources. CH4'S coal seam gas resources are
sourced from Authorities to Prospect ("ATP's") which cover over 7,000km of the Northern Bowen
Basin. The location of these tenements is illustrated in Figure 1.2.
CH4'S initial project is the Moranbah Gas Project (MGP), and is located in Central Queensland's
Bowen Basin, approximately 170km west of Mackay. The Moranbah Gas Project is located within
PL191, a 219km petroleum lease, and commenced development in August 2003.
The project is a 50:50 Joint Venture with BHP Billiton, and is operated by CH4.
Each operational well has been designed to use a single vertical production well, and with two
surface to in seam horizontal wells. The horizontal surface to in-seam holes are drilled in a chevron
pattern to intersect the production zone of the vertical well.

1.2 Location, Purpose and Design
1.2.1 Location:
The Moranbah Gas Project is situated adjacent to the township of Moranbah. GM008 is located
immediately to north of Moranbah, adjacent to the Goonyella Road. The locations of GMOO8V,
GM008A and GM008B are shown in Figure 1.3.
1.2.2 Purpose:
GM008 is a CBM Production Well targeting gas from the Goonyella Middle Seam.
1.2.3 Design:
The vertical production well (GM008V) is intersected by two surface to in seam lateral wells
(GM008A and GMOO8B) using directional drilling techniques. This type of well design is referred to
as the 'chevron' pattern. Another lateral (GM008C) was later planned to be added. This well was
abandoned though soon after drilling commenced.

8.Text: PL191 is located on the northwestern flank of the Permo-Triassic Bowen Basin in Central
Queensland. The sedimentary strata in this area were deposited on the Collinsville Shelf, a stable
tectonic environment situated to the west of the major depositiona axis of the northern Bowen
The area is mantled by an irregular cover of poorly consolidated Tertiary sedimentary strata and
both fresh and weathered basalt of the Suttor Formation. The Tertiary cover overlies the Triassic
sediments of the Mimosa Group, which in turn overlies the sediments and main coal-bearing units
of the Late Permian Blackwater Group (refer to Table 2.1).
The Late Permian Blackwater Group is divided into three terrestrial units, namely the Moranbah
Coal Measures, Fort Cooper Coal Measures, and the Rangal Coal Measures.

The primary coal measure sequences targeted for exploration and production within the CH4
tenement areas are these three coal measures. The stratigraphic relationship is shown above, in
The Rangal Coal Measures (RCM) conformably overly the Fort Cooper Coal Measures, and are
targeted elsewhere by CH4 as a potentia gas resource. The RCM are typically 150 metres thick,
with two main coal seams ranging in thickness from 3 to 9 metres.
The Fort Cooper Coal Measures (FCCM) are approximately 400 m in thickness, and comprise
sediments including coal, sandstones, siltstones and mudstones. The FCCM coals are
characterised by up to seven seams varying in thickness from 6 to 60m. Their high inherent ash
ratios, and abundant associated tuffaceous beds distinguish the FCCM coal seams.
Despite the FCCM's low gross to net coal ratio and poor permeability's, they represent a potential
gas resource. The FCCM conformably overlie the MCM.

The Moranbah Coal Measures (MCM) are the main target for coal seam gas exploration and
production within PL191. The MCM consist of coals, sandstones, siltstones and shales; and range
in thickness from 250-300m.
The MCM have an aggregate coal thickness of approximately 15m, are characterised by several
laterally persistent, relatively thick coal seams interspersed with several thin minor seams. Most
partings are thin tuffaceous claystone.
Four seams within the MCM are considered seam gas targets, based on their thickness, continuity
and physical characteristics: the "Q" Seams, "P" Seam, Goonyella Middle (GM) and Goonyella
Lower (GL) seams.
The P-Tuff bed is located between the P and GM seams. This is a regionally extensive marker bed
and is an important unit for correlation due to its characteristically high natural gamma signature.
The MCM and coal seams contained within the sequence generally strike N-S, and dip uniformly to
the east between 3 and 5o. Localised areas of steeper dip also occur in association with structural
features, and the seams are displaced by normal and reverse structures with throws of up to 15
metres.
Within PL191 the MCM is unconformably obscured by an irregular mantle of poorly consolidated
Cainozoic cover, characterised by sedimentary strata, such as river gravels, clays, and sands, and
both fresh and weathered basalt.
The Cainozoic cover ranges in thickness from less than 10m thick, up to 100m thick along the
southwestern margin of PL191, where basalt has in filled deeply incised Tertiary palaeo-channels.
2.3 Site Geology and Stratigraphy
The Goonyella Middle (GM) seam of the MCM is the main target for coal seam production for
The GM seam is regionally extensive in the northern Bowen Basin. Within the PL 191 area, it is
typically 5m in thickness, but does thin to the southeast as a result of seam splitting. Immediately
south of PL 191, the GM seam it averages 4m or less in thickness.
Within the PL 191 area, the GM seam is broadly folded. A central anticline is flanked by
northeasterly plunging synclines, with shallow dips on flanks of generally between 3o and 5o.
Localised steepening of seam and bedding dips occur, usually proximal to small-scale faults and
structures within the PL area. Faults throws have been seen to have up to 15 metres vertical
displacement.

3.0 Drilling Technique
3.1 Drilling Technique
The directional drilling technique employed by CH4 involves drilling a vertical Production Well,
which is generally intersected by two Surface to in Seam lateral wells.
The vertical Production Well is drilled to intersect the target coal seam (usually about 250 to 450
metres vertical depth). After spud Steel Conductor casing and steel Tertiary casing (to below the
depth of Cainozoic cover) are set and cemented in place, and production casing set to just above
the roof of the target seam. The vertical well is under reamed to 30" or 16" diameter over the
targeted coal seam interval.
Two lateral holes are drilled from surface to intersect the vertical production well. Total surface to in
seam hole lengths are in the order of 1500 1900 metres, depending on depth of seam and hence
length of radius bend section.
The lateral holes have Conductor, Tertiary and Radius Bend sections cased with steel and
cemented in place. The lateral wells are drilled in a 'chevron' pattern with an angular separation
between them typically around 50 degrees. This reduces the number of vertical well and wellhead
completions required.
The in-seam holes provide a clear path for water to be pumped out via the vertical wel and for gas
to travel to the surface. The holes are planned and drilled to have up to 1,200m in coal.
3.2 Drilling Summary
GM008 is located northwest of Moranbah in the northern Bowen Basin, Queensland within
Petroleum Lease PL191. GM008 comprises a vertica hole (GM008V) and 2 lateral surface to in-
seam holes (GM008A & GMO08B) as seen in Figure 1.2. An additional lateral to in-seam hole,
GM008C was drilled. It was abandoned after 98m.
GM008 was drilled as a production well in Phase One of the Moranbah Gas Project, with methane
drainage from the Goonyella Middle seam (GM) found within the Moranbah Coal Measures (MCM).
Mitchell Drilling Contractors was bought to site to complete the three-hole program, with Surtron
Technologies providing the required steering support.
Daily Drilling Reports, which summarise the day-to-day progress of the wells, are found in Appendix
1. Table 4.3 gives a summary of the drilling products used on each well.

GMO05A was spudded on the 6th of March 2004 and was later drilled to a depth of 1443.72m
where it intersected the vertical well, GM008V. Separate rigs were used to drill the pre collar,
radius bend and the in seam sections of the hole.
Rig # 111 and driller K. Hunter arrived onsite on the 6th of March to drill the pre collar section of the
hole. A 10" bit was used to drill out 6m initially which was later cased with an 8 5/8" casing to the
same depth. The hole was extended to 144.46m with an 8" bit and was cased down to 144m with
a 5/8" casing. The rig moved offsite on the 10th of March 2004.
Rig # 107 and drillers D. Bull and D. Smith moved onsite on the 24th of March 2004 to complete the
radius bend portion of the hole. All bits used on this rig were 5 7/8". A tri cone bit was initially used
to drill out half a metre of cement before deepening the hole to 146m. A PCD and down hole motor
was then used to further the hole to 242m. This hole was later cemented up to 125m. A tri cone bit
was used again to drill the concrete out from 125 to 160m before another PCD/DHM assemblage
was used down to 206m. The hole was again cemented up to 140m and the initial trajectory of the
hole was abandoned. The tri cone bit was again used to drill out the cement from 140-160m which
was followed by PCD/DHM assemblage that deepened the hole to 422m. The change in the
trajectory of the hole led to a spooned section being created. The hole passed through the GM
seam from 221.44-239m before re-entering the seam at 413.53m. Steel 4 1/2" casing was then
installed in the hole down to 412.96m, the last 3m of which were fibreglass. 4 1/2" steel casing was
left in-seam however, from 221.44 to 239.44 (18 metres). The rig moved offsite on the 19th of April
Rig # 104 and driller D. Fisher, L. Hoare and S. Bredhaver moved onsite on the 22rd of April 2004 to
complete the in-seam section of the hole. A 96mm PCD and down hole motor assemblage was
used. Due to the previous spoon, there was a roof touch between 437.53 and 527.53m. There
were few other roof or floor touches were encountered (Table 3.4.1). The hole intersected the
vertical well, GM008V, at a depth of 1443.72. Rods and BHA tripped out and NRQ pipe tripped in.
Poly pipe was run into to the end of the hole and anchored in the under reamed section of GMOO8V
with a poly dart. The total in-seam length of the hole is 964.19m. The rig was demobilised on the
30th of April 2004.
